 School, founded by Tapping Reeve","link_text":"Sarah Burr Reeve"},{"related_id":"HD3158","type":"civic_connection","display_label":"Appointed Percival as state geologist 1835","link_text":"James Gates Percival"}],"gender":"male","notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"27th and 29th Governor of Connecticut; US Senator","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_W._Edwards"},"narrative_blocks":[{"header":"Twice Governor of Connecticut, US Senator, Edwards grandson","detail":"Yale-educated (Princeton B.A. 1797) and a Litchfield Law School graduate, Edwards also served as US Representative 1819-1823 and as Connecticut State Senate president and Speaker of the Connecticut House. His mother Frances Ogden (X00654) was from a prominent New Jersey family; his father Pierpont Edwards (H00386) was a Yale judge and Continental Congress delegate. His sister Henrietta Frances Edwards (HD2046) married Eli Whitney, inventor of the cotton gin. His niece Henrietta Whitney Edwards (X00160) married Worthington Hooker (H01407) — a previously unrecognized convergence of the Hooker and Edwards lines. (Wikipedia; EH 1909)","body":"Henry Waggaman Edwards served as the 27th and 29th Governor of Connecticut (1833-1834 and 1835-1838) and as a US Senator (1823-1827), making him the most politically prominent of Pierpont Edwards's sons.","number":1,"category":"politics"},{"header":"Trained at Litchfield Law School by Tapping Reeve","detail":"The school founded by his relative-by-marriage trained some of the most prominent American lawyers and politicians of the early republic — among them Aaron Burr Jr., who studied under Reeve before Reeve married Burr's sister. The Litchfield Law School network running through the Hooker-Edwards-Burr family is one of the densest institutional cross-connections in the entire tree. (EH 1909; Wikipedia)","body":"Edwards studied law at Litchfield Law School, founded by Tapping Reeve — who had married Sally Burr Reeve, sister of Aaron Burr Jr. and great-aunt of Edwards himself.","number":2,"category":"education"},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Daughter Henrietta married fellow Hooker descendant Worthington Hooker","body":"His daughter Henrietta Whitney Edwards married Worthington Hooker, bringing his Edwards-Pierpont line back into convergence with the Hooker descent. Their marriage produced a Hooker double-descent generation."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Funded the Percival geological survey during second governorship","body":"During his second governorship in 1835, Connecticut became the first state to fund a comprehensive geological survey. He appointed James Gates Percival — a fellow Hooker descendant — as state geologist; the resulting survey took seven years across two-mile intervals."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"bio":{"display_name":"Henry Waggaman Edwards","first_name":"Henry","last_name":"Edwards","middle_name":"Waggaman","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777482767/HenryWEdwards__3x4a_grvp1y.jpg"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST024","relationship":"alumnus","institution_blurb":"Studied law as Tapping Reeve's grand-nephew through the Burr connection."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":["ART048"],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":[],"education":[],"career":[],"is_placeholder":false,"slug":"henry-edwards-1779"},"X00656":{"id":"X00656","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD2045","children_ids":["HD2047","HD2048","X00160","HD2100","HD2101","HD2102","HD2103"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1801}],"birth":{"year":1778,"month":8,"day":16},"deat